<HEADLINE>
<P>
HARNESS RACING RETURNS TO LOS ALAMITOS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Harness racing will return to Southern California tonight at Los Alamitos Race 
Course. 
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Lloyd Arnold completed the purchase of the track for $71 
million from Hollywood Park, which bought it from Millie Vessels in 1983. 
Arnold managed harness races at Los Alamitos from 1979 to 1983. 
</P>
<P>
Racing will be held on Tuesday through Saturday through April 21, starting 
nightly at 7:30. 
</P>
<P>
Arnold said the track has spent more than $400,000 on renovations, including 
600 new chairs and 100 televisions in the Turf Club. 
</P>
<P>
Part of Arnold's marketing strategy will be to improve the sport's public 
image, which has been damaged by allegations of race fixing. 
</P>
<P>
"Qualified drivers with past suspicions, but no proof of wrongdoing, will start 
the meeting with a clean slate," he said. "But all drivers have been put on 
notice that if something doesn't look right, they're gone immediately. We have 
$71 million invested and we don't want to be put out by a few bad apples." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
