<HEADLINE>
<P>
CLOTHESLINES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARYLOU LUTHER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Question: My husband works in Manhattan and is due for a new coat. He wants to 
buy a Chesterfield, and I feel that style is too dressy for a lawyer with a lot 
of conservative clients. Please comment. -- R.R.O. 
</P>
<P>
Answer: Chesterfields are the comeback coat of the season in menswear. Perhaps 
your husband will find this advice from the coat's namesake, 19th-Century Earl 
of Chesterfield, as valid today as when it was written in 1840: "Take great 
care always to be dressed like the reasonable people of your own age; in the 
place where you are; whose dress is never spoken of one way or another as 
either too negligent or too much studied." 
</P>
<P>
The Chesterfield with its slight shaping and velvet collar is available in 
traditional gray and navy herringbones as well as such unexpected colors as 
taupe and olive. 
</P>
<P>
 Luther, a Times syndicated columnist, welcomes questions from readers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
