<HEADLINE>
<P>
DR. JOYCE BROTHERS: WHEN A WIFE IS ADDICTED TO SEX 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DR. JOYCE BROTHERS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DEAR DR. BROTHERS: My 40-year-old wife was always an exceptionally beautiful 
woman, but she was never sexually promiscuous until recently. Since I still 
love her, this pains me and causes me considerable embarrassment. She claims 
she's addicted to sex and that she can never get enough. Is this possible, and, 
if so, what does it mean? F.K. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR F.K.: Before I answer this question, I'd like to know if you've talked 
with your wife about what's happening in your marriage, if you've asked her why 
she feels there was this sudden change and if she has any theories on why she 
feels "addicted" now but never before? 
</P>
<P>
It's possible for people to be addicted to sex. Those who are use sex as an 
escape for their problems in much the same way other addicts reach for their 
"fix." There's little doubt that women who've been great beauties have an 
especially difficult time with the aging process. Unfortunately, remarkable 
beauties often fail to develop their potential because they get used to relying 
on their beauty even as small girls. If you have valued your wife primarily for 
her beauty, she may be concerned that you're losing interest as you witness her 
beauty fade. 
</P>
<P>
She may be using sexual conquests as a way to reassure herself that she's still 
attractive. If you want to salvage your marriage, get professional help. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR DR. BROTHERS: My son-in-law is physically abusive to my daughter. She 
won't leave him because she feels she can get him to change if he stops 
drinking. Each time, after he hits her, he swears it won't happen again and 
each time he tells her he'll stop drinking. This last time, he bet his entire 
bank account that he won't touch another drop and that he'll never under any 
circumstances hit her. What do you think the chances are that he'll keep his 
promise? G.W. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR G.W.: Not good. This isn't to say that this man isn't capable of change, 
but unless he is highly motivated and gets the help he needs, there's little 
chance that he'll suddenly become the kind of man your daughter wants. 
</P>
<P>
First of all, his abuse of alcohol isn't necessarily linked to his abuse of 
your daughter. Alcoholics may sometimes blame spouse abuse on alcohol, but 
studies indicate that abstention alone doesn't solve the problem. If this man 
is an alcoholic, then he should become a part of the Alcoholic Anonymous 
program, go to meetings every evening and dedicate himself to living their 
doctrine one day at a time. This will undoubtedly help him gain control of his 
temper, but I suspect he also needs special therapy to teach him how to talk 
constructively about what upsets him and now to deal with his rage in a 
positive way, rather than simply striking out at a convenient target, usually 
someone or something weaker and smaller. 
</P>
</TEXT>
