</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE GALLERIES: SANTA MONICA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SUVAN GEER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ironically, Donald Lipski's large untitled assemblage begins to breed life from 
industrial materials. A mammoth braid of nylon rope tied like a pony tail 
strongly suggests a sperm; a long glass pipe filled with water and pink rubber 
bands looks like intestines clogged with worms; a hovering steel-wool blimp 
high on the gallery wall recalls a strangely mechanical deep sea sponge. 
</P>
<P>
Lipski's artistic forays as a mad scientist have the spark of life, but lead a 
curiously tense existence. His female-shaped bass cello case with red fluid in 
its belly is suspended by a bail picker like a prisoner of the Inquisition. His 
two white, steel pylons bolted to big chunks of wood put a vise grip on the 
verdant book titled "Meat Under the Microscope"; they have enough aerobic 
pressure to make the whitewashed wood look flush with fresh blood. 
</P>
<P>
Biological allusions are frequently subtle: as much due to the weird visual 
logic created by the assemblage as to the hardware the artist uses. Pieces give 
the gallery the feel of an underwater junkyard where derelict devices have 
combined via spontaneous generation. Human Angst seems to have been genetically 
imprinted on these things when they were originally machined and Lipski 
unleashes it effortlessly with the assembly. Ultimately, that gives the work a 
biting cynicism. (Dorothy Goldeen Gallery, 1547 9th St., to Dec. 30.) SUVAN 
GEER 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Art Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA112489-0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 139332 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
November 24, 1989, Friday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Part F; Page 20; Column 4; Entertainment Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
344 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE GALLERIES: WILSHIRE CENTER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CATHY CURTIS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the '50s, art patron Peggy Guggenheim jokingly used to admonish sculptor 
Claire Falkenstein, "Now go home and do your knitting." In fact, the artist was 
painstakingly welding iron wire or bands fused with chunks of glass to create 
dense, glinting sculptural webs suggestive of molecular structure and 
biological growth patterns. Her affinity for fields of energy and rhythmic 
patterning -- visible even in early representational drawings -- was well 
suited to translating news from the world of science into tangible imagery. 
</P>
<P>
A zingy group of works from the past 60 years by Falkenstein -- still active at 
80 -- gives an idea of the breadth of her technically adventurous creations. 
They range from "Fluids in Motion" (1947), a Plexiglas relief lit by 
fluorescent lights, to "Predator" (1963), two tightly "knitted" enameled iron 
forms that surround, and are engulfed by, a shopping cart. Falkenstein welded 
slumping green glass wine jugs to metal ("Four Within a Structure"), painted on 
X-ray film ("Game") and made a shaped wood painting in 1948, decades before 
that approach was sanctioned by the contemporary art Establishment. When you 
plug in "Planet Mars" (1962), a piece of plastic filled with mercury glows red 
and yellow behind a scruffy tangle of painted iron. 
</P>
<P>
If some of her experiments seem rather clunky and quaint today, other pieces 
remain impressive. "Cellular" (1941), for which the artist made her own 
double-triangle frame, offers an engrossing play of shapes transformed from 
nature (a foot, a planet, an orbit), painted in a luscious medley of stinging 
green, salmon, lemon and pale purple. Even "DNA Molecule" (1970-71) -- 
concentric networks of curving copper forms twinkling with Venetian glass -- is 
hard to resist as it slowly and solemnly circles in opposing directions. It is 
a tribute to the optimism and investigative energies of the American modernist 
vision, of which Falkenstein remains a vigorous, witty and superbly intelligent 
proponent. (Jack Rutberg Fine Arts, Inc., 357 N. La Brea Ave., to Dec. 23.) 
CATHY CURTIS 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Art Review 
</P>
