<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE SIDELINES; 
</P>
<P>
GREEN SHOOTS DAY'S BEST SCORE FOR ONE-STROKE LEAD IN JAPAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
KAIMONCHO, Japan 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
American Hubert Green shot a 67 -- the day's best score -- for a one-stroke 
lead today at the halfway mark of the $714,000 Casio World Open golf 
tournament. 
</P>
<P>
Green, winner of the tournament in 1985, sank a 6-foot birdie putt on the 
508-yard, par-5 18th hole to wrest the lead from first-round pacesetter 
Naomichi Ozaki of Japan. 
</P>
<P>
Green also had seven birdies and three bogeys over the 7,014-yard, par-72 
Kaimon course of the Ibusuki Golf Club. He completed the two trips at 135, 9 
under par. 
</P>
<P>
"I am now in top shape," Green said. "I'm shooting at will, and my putting was 
also pretty good." 
</P>
<P>
Ozaki, coming off consecutive second-place finishes, carded a 70. Toru Nakamura 
of Japan was alone in third place at 137. 
</P>
<P>
Larry Mize, winner of last week's Dunlop Phoenix tournament, shot a 71 to drop 
to a fourth-place tie with fellow American Mark Calcavecchia at 138. The 
British Open champion carded a 69. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Hubert Green 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief; Game Story; Wire 
</P>
